<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Image Processing |</title><link>https://ehsan-ami.github.io/tags/image-processing/</link><atom:link href="https://ehsan-ami.github.io/tags/image-processing/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><description>Image Processing</description><generator>Hugo Blox Builder (https://hugoblox.com)</generator><language>en-us</language><lastBuildDate>Wed, 01 Aug 2018 20:09:22 -0600</lastBuildDate><image><url>https://ehsan-ami.github.io/media/icon_hu_da05098ef60dc2e7.png</url><title>Image Processing</title><link>https://ehsan-ami.github.io/tags/image-processing/</link></image><item><title>Painter Robot</title><link>https://ehsan-ami.github.io/projects/painter_robot/</link><pubDate>Wed, 01 Aug 2018 20:09:22 -0600</pubDate><guid>https://ehsan-ami.github.io/projects/painter_robot/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;During my stay at the University of Trieste in Italy, I have worked on the painter robot project under the supervision of Dr. Gallina. In this project, I have developed a novel optimized non-photorealistic rendering method which is inspired by Painterly algorithm. Utilizing the new method minimizes brush strokes overlapping on the canvas and decreases the cost of operation time. Additionally, I have also developed a python interface which gets brush strokes as the input data and paints them on the canvas by controlling a UR10 arm robot using MoveIt and ROS.&lt;/p&gt;
